or gather’) + <i>pep(p)er</i> ‘pepper’, probably an occupational name for a herbalist or spicer."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Eleanor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Eleanor Culpeper was born about 1383, her father, Sir Thomas Culpeper, was 29 and her mother, Alianor de Grene, was 26. She had at least 2 sons and 2 daughters with Sir Reginald Cobham 3rd Baron Cobham. She died in 1422, at the age of 40, and was buried in Lingfield, Surrey, England."},"et":{"about 1383–1422":"umbes 1383–1422","1381–1430":"1381–1430","1383–1422":"1383–1422","1382–1446":"1382–1446","1406–1441":"1406–1441","1410–1452":"1410–1452","1419–145